message: This page is solely talking about MD and DO degrees. The AMA advocates for those two degrees as degrees of a medical doctor. Both degrees are given by schools registered in the World Directory of Medical Schools. DPM is not a recognized medical degree; having no right to participate in ACGME-accredited residencies, take USMLE, and not going to a WDMS-registered school, DPMs are not to be talked about in this article.

Podiatrists do not qualify to participate in medical (ACGME) residencies. Since a degree in podiatry is not in practicing equivalency to that of a medical doctor (someone who holds a medical degree; see "physician" or "medical degree" in Wiki spaces), they should not be generalized with physicians.
Important updates about PG training of DO physicians and clear distinction between osteopathy and osteopathic medicine.

This page summarizes medical degrees that allow the for the unrestricted practice of allopathic medicine and surgery in its undergraduate and graduate section of degrees. DPM degree does not provide the same privilege as the other degrees listed in the graduate medical degree section; the scope of practice for DPM is limited. Furthermore, DPM degree granting schools are not listed as medical schools in the World Directory of Medical Schools. DPM holders cannot take USMLE or do ACGME residency.

There is nothing in this world called "osteopathic physician-neurosurgeon." Dr. Sheppard was a neurosurgeon with a D.O. degree. His specialty already proves that he is a medical/osteopathic physician; restating that is redundant.
S. S. Still was not an osteopathic physician; he was a non-physician osteopath, similar to what we find today outside of the USA.
/* Education */ Dr. S. S. Still did not hold the modern-day DO degree; at the time of his graduation, the AAO was only giving Diploma of Osteopathy degrees out.

He is an EM doctor; his specialty already proves that he is a medical/osteopathic physician, which does not appropriately describe his occupation. Once a doctor specializes, he/she is referred to by that specialist title.

She is a gastroenterologist; that already explains that he is a medical/osteopathic physician. Once a physician specializes in something, it is redundant to address him/her by any occupation but what he/she specializes in.

He is a neurologist; that already explains that he is a medical/osteopathic physician. Once a physician specializes in something, it is redundant to address him by any occupation but what he/she specializes oin

The American Academy of Nurse Anesthesiology defines their board certified nurses as CRNA, or "Certified Registered Nurse Anesthetist." As per the organization, their headline says "Join one of the fastest-growing ... careers in the U.S. as a Certified Registered Nurse Anesthetist." The AANA's motto says, "Be a Nurse. Be a Nurse Anesthetist." While AANA uses anesthesiology in its name to signify the field they work in, it doesn't call its members anesthesiologists, a term signifying physicians.

Dr. Kamaleswar Mukherjee has an active medical registration with the Medical Council of India under the jurisdiction of the West Bengal Medical Council. His registration no. is 53647, which is public info. Under such situations, his description should contain his identity as a physician.

message: An MD degree from the US is recognized school by school in foreign countries. Aruba, for instance, only accepts an MD granted by 5 US schools. The AOA has renovated its International Bureau since 2016 to aid USDOs gain practicing rights worldwide; AMOCA was once such initiative that added 20 previously non-participating countries.
